{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655559"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:03:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:03:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18676"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18676"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76798"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11408"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62297"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10329"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26432"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76798"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMechanoreceptors in the skin are responsible for detecting different types of mechanical stimuli. These receptors vary in their adaptation rates and optimal stimulus frequencies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of Pacinian corpuscles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Detection of high-frequency vibration","Detection of low-frequency vibration","Detection of sustained pressure","Detection of joint position","Detection of skin stretch"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPacinian corpuscles are specialised mechanoreceptors that primarily function in the \u003Cstrong\u003Edetection of high-frequency vibration\u003C/strong\u003E. They are rapidly adapting receptors that respond optimally to frequencies between 200-300 Hz. Their distinctive onion-like layered structure allows them to detect rapid changes in pressure and vibration.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of skin stretch\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily detected by Ruffini endings\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of low-frequency vibration\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of Meissner corpuscles which optimally detect frequencies between 20-50 Hz\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of sustained pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - This is detected by slowly adapting mechanoreceptors like Merkel cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of joint position\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily detected by proprioceptors in muscles and joints, not cutaneous mechanoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe rapid adaptation of Pacinian corpuscles makes them particularly suited for detecting vibration and quick pressure changes, while being relatively insensitive to sustained stimuli.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pacinian corpuscles detect high-frequency vibration and pressure changes in the skin.","Meissner corpuscles detect low-frequency vibration and light touch.","Different mechanoreceptors in the skin are specialised for detecting specific types of mechanical stimuli."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"item